# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-slicing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The 3GPP specification 38 series provides the technical details behind 5G NR, the successor of LTE.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The study of 5G NR within 3GPP started in 2015, and the first specification was made available by the end of 2017.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] While the 3GPP standardization process was ongoing, the industry had already begun efforts to implement infrastructure compliant with the draft standard, with the first large-scale commercial launch of 5G NR having occurred in the end of 2018.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Since 2019, many operators have deployed 5G NR networks and handset manufacturers have developed 5G NR enabled handsets.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] A "Non-Standalone" (NSA) gNodeB is built on an existing LTE (4G) base station (eNodeB or eNB).
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Ooredoo was the first carrier to launch a commercial 5G NR network, in May 2018 in Qatar.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Other carriers around the world have been following suit.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] In 2018, 3GPP published Release 15, which includes what is described as "Phase 1" standardization for 5G NR.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The timeline for Release 16, which will be "5G phase 2", follows a freeze date of March 2020 and a completion date of June 2020, Release 17 was originally scheduled for delivery in September 2021. but, because of the COVID-19 pandemic, it was rescheduled for June 2022.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Rel.18 is referred to as "NR Advanced" signifying another milestone in wireless communication systems.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] NR Advanced will include features such as eXtended Reality (XR), AI/ML studies, and Mobility enhancements.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Mobility is in the core of 3GPP technology and has so far been handled on Layer 3 (RRC), now, in Rel-18 the work on mobility is to introduce lower layer triggered mobility.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Initial 5G NR launches will depend on existing LTE infrastructure in non-standalone (NSA) mode, before maturation of the standalone (SA) mode with the 5G core network.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Additionally, the spectrum can be dynamically shared between LTE and 5G NR.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] To make better use of existing assets, carriers may opt to dynamically share it between LTE and 5G NR.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The spectrum is multiplexed over time between both generations of mobile networks depending on user demand, while still using the LTE network for control functions.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Dynamic spectrum sharing (DSS) may be deployed on existing LTE equipment as long as it is compatible with 5G NR.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Only the 5G NR terminal needs to be compatible with DSS.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The non-standalone (NSA) mode of 5G NR refers to an option of 5G NR deployment that depends on the control plane of an existing LTE network for control functions, while 5G NR is exclusively focused on the user plane.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] This is reported to speed up 5G adoption, however some operators and vendors have criticized prioritizing the introduction of 5G NR NSA on the grounds that it could hinder the implementation of the standalone mode of the network.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] It uses the same core network as a 4G network, but with upgraded radio equipment.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The standalone (SA) mode of 5G NR refers to using 5G cells for both signalling and information transfer, essentially a 5G network without any legacy 4G infrastructure.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] It includes the new 5G Packet Core architecture instead of relying on the 4G Evolved Packet Core, to allow the deployment of 5G without the LTE network.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] It is expected to have lower cost, better efficiency, and to assist development of new use cases.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] However, initial deployment might see slower speed than existing network due to the allocation of spectrum.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] It uses a new core network dedicated to 5G.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] The length of the cyclic prefix is inversely proportional to the subcarrier spacing.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] It is 4.7 μs with 15 kHz, and 4.7 / 16 = 0.29 μs for 240 kHz subcarrier spacing.
[src:network-slicing/5g-nr] Additionally, higher subcarrier spacings allow for reduced latency and increased support for high-frequency bands, essential for the ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) and enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) applications in 5G.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] For this reason, this technology assumes a central role to support 5G mobile networks that are designed to efficiently embrace a plethora of services with very different service level requirements (SLR).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The realization of this service-oriented view of the network leverages on the concepts of software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) that allow the implementation of flexible and scalable network slices on top of a common network infrastructure.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] From a business model perspective, each network slice is administrated by a mobile virtual network operator (MVNO).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The infrastructure provider (the owner of the telecommunication infrastructure) leases its physical resources to the MVNOs that share the underlying physical network.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] According to the availability of the assigned resources, a MVNO can autonomously deploy multiple network slices that are customized to the various applications provided to its own users.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The history of network slicing can be tracked back to the late 1980s with the introduction of the concept of "slice" in the networking field.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Overlay networks provided the first form of network slicing since heterogeneous network resources were combined to create virtual networks over a common infrastructure.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] However, they lacked a mechanism that could enable their programmability.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] In the early 2000s, PlanetLab introduced a virtualization framework that allowed groups of users to program network functions in order to obtain isolated and application-specific slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The advent of SDN technologies in 2009 further extended the programmability capabilities via open interfaces that enabled the realization of fully configurable and scalable network slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] In the context of mobile networks, network slicing evolved from the concept of RAN sharing that was initially introduced in the LTE standard.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Examples of such technology are multi-operator radio access networks (MORAN) and multi-operator core networks (MOCN), which allow network operators to share common LTE resources within the same radio access network (RAN).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Network slicing emerges as an essential technique in 5G networks to accommodate such different and possibly contrasting quality of service (QoS) requirements exploiting a single physical network infrastructure.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The basic idea of network slicing is to "slice" the original network architecture in multiple logical and independent networks that are configured to effectively meet the various services requirements.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] In commercial terms, network slicing allows a mobile operator to create specific virtual networks that cater to particular clients and use cases.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Certain applications - such as mobile broadband, machine-to-machine communications (e.g. in manufacturing or logistics), or smart cars - will benefit from leveraging different aspects of 5G technology.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] One might require higher speeds, another low latency, and yet another access to edge computing resources.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] By creating separate slices that prioritise specific resources a 5G operator can offer tailored solutions to particular industries.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Some sources insist this will revolutionise industries like marketing, augmented reality, or mobile gaming, while others are more cautious, pointing to unevenness in network coverage and poor reach of advantages beyond increased speed.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Slicing will be very useful to MVNOs as different use cases can be supported in a layer based on parameters like low latency high speed for video streaming for OTT focused MVNOs, similarly telemetry operations could have lower speed parameter and as on.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Although there are different proposals of network slice architectures, it is possible to define a general architecture that maps the common elements of each solution into a general and unified framework.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] From a high-level perspective, the network slicing architecture can be considered as composed of two mains blocks, one dedicated to the actual slice implementation and the other dedicated to the slice management and configuration.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The first block is designed as a multi-tier architecture composed by three layers (service layer, network function layer, infrastructure layer), where each one contributes to the slice definition and deployment with distinct tasks.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The second block is designed as a centralized network entity, generically denoted as *network slice controller*, that monitors and manages the functionalities between the three layers in order to efficiently coordinate the coexistence of multiple slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The service layer interfaces directly with the network business entities (e.g.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] MVNOs and 3rd party service providers) that share the underlying physical network and it provides a unified vision of the service requirements.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Each service is formally represented as *service instance*, which embeds all the network characteristics in the form of SLA requirements that are expected to be fully satisfied by a suitable slice creation.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The network function layer is in charge of the creation of each network slice according to service instance requests coming from the upper layer.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] It is composed of a set of *network functions* that embody well-defined behaviors and interfaces.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Multiple network functions are placed over the virtual network infrastructure and chained together to create an end-to-end network slice instance that reflects the network characteristics requested by the service.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The configuration of the network functions are performed by means of a set of *network operations* that allow management of their full lifecycle (from their placement when a slice is created to their de-allocation when the function provided is no longer needed).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] To increase resource usage efficiency, the same network function can be simultaneously shared by different slices at the cost of an increase in the complexity of operations management.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Conversely, a one-to-one mapping between each network function and each slice eases the configuration procedures, but can lead to poor and inefficient resource usage.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The infrastructure layer represents the actual physical network topology (radio access network, transport network and core network) upon which every network slice is multiplexed and it provides the physical network resources to host the several network functions composing each slice.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The network domain of the available resources includes a heterogeneous set of infrastructure components like data centers (storage and computation capacity resources), devices enabling network connectivity such as routers (networking resources) and base stations (radio bandwidth resources).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The network slice controller is defined as a network orchestrator, which interfaces with the various functionalities performed by each layer to coherently manage each slice request.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The benefit of such network element is that it enables an efficient and flexible slice creation that can be reconfigured during its life-cycle.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Due to the complexity of the performed tasks which address different purposes, the network slice controller can be composed by multiple orchestrators that independently manage a subset of functionalities of each layer.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] To fulfill the service requirements, the various orchestration entities need to coordinate with each other by exchanging high-level information about the state of the operations involved in the slice creation and deployment.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Slice isolation is an important requirement that allows enforcing the core concept of network slicing about the simultaneous coexistence of multiple slices sharing the same infrastructure.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] This property is achieved by imposing that each slice's performance must not have any impact on the other slice's performance.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Slicing has become an important part of 5G networks, but it doesn't have to forget to guarantee the QoS.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Some studies have demonstrated that formulating the problem with the QoS as a stochastic problem, permit us to maximize the average throughput of the AP, while satisfying the constraints related to the QoS.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Monetizing 5G services faster is one of the topics that interests network operators the most because the costs of building and maintaining 5G networks are high, and it's difficult to predict the demand for 5G services.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] 5G network slicing is one of the effective ways to offer customized services for different industries such as manufacturing, transportation, and healthcare.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Combined with AIOps, ML/AI-driven automation and 5G lifecycle optimization, it can reduce OpEx and increase revenues for network operators.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] In the 3GPP 5G core architecture, the user plane and control plane functions are separated.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Control plane capabilities, for instance, session management, access authentication, policy management, and user data storage are independent of the user plane functionality.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The user plane handles packet forwarding, encapsulation or de-capsulation, and associated transport level specifics.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] This separation leads to the distribution of the user plane functions close to the edge of network slices (e.g., so as to reduce latency) and to be independent of the control plane.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The AMF (as a function of the CP) controls UEs that have been authenticated to use the services of the operator and manages the mobility of the UEs across the gNBs.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The SMF (again part of the CP) manages the sessions of UEs, while AMF transmits the session management messages between the UEs and SMF.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] UPF (as part of the UP) performs the processing and forwarding of the user data.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] NSSF (as a function of the CP) is responsible for the management and orchestration of network slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] CSMF (as a function of the CP) translates the requirements of services to requirements relating to network slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] 5G Core network functions can be sliced to support specific services for different UEs.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Thanks to the modular nature of the 5G core, the network functions of the 5G core can be split and shared between different network slices to reduce management complexity.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] In general, we can perform 5G core network slicing in two ways.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] We can implement dedicated core network functions per network slice.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] In this architecture, each network slice has a set of completely dedicated core network functions (e.g., AUSF, AMF, SMF, and UDM).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The UEs can access various services from network slices and different core networks.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Alternatively, we can share some control plane functions between the network slices while others such as user plane functions are slice specific (e.g., UPF).
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] AMF is usually shared by several network slices, while SMF and UPF are usually dedicated to specific network slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The AMF function will be shared between different network slices in order to reduce the mobility management signaling when the UE uses the services of different network slices simultaneously.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] For example, UE location management or the control signaling between the UE and the old AMF will be reduced when it will be connected to the new AMF of another network slice.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Also, UDM and NSSF are typically shared by all network slices to reduce the management complexity of network slices.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] The emergence of network slicing also exposes novel security and privacy challenges, primarily related to aspects such as network slicing life-cycle security, inter-slice security, intra-slice security, slice broker security, zero-touch network and management security, and blockchain security.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Therefore, enhancing the security, privacy, and trust of network slicing has become a key research area toward realizing the true capabilities of 5G.
[src:network-slicing/network-slicing] Various security solutions are proposed for resolving the security threats, challenges, and issues of network slicing.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] In computing, **network virtualization** is the process of combining hardware and software network resources and network functionality into a single, software-based administrative entity, a **virtual network**.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Network virtualization involves platform virtualization, often combined with resource virtualization.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Network virtualization is categorized as either **external virtualization**, combining many networks or parts of networks into a virtual unit, or **internal virtualization**, providing network-like functionality to software containers on a single network server.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] In software testing, software developers use network virtualization to test software which are under development in a simulation of the network environments in which the software is intended to operate.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] As a component of application performance engineering, network virtualization enables developers to emulate connections between applications, services, dependencies, and end users in a test environment without having to physically test the software on all possible hardware or system software.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] The validity of the test depends on the accuracy of the network virtualization in emulating real hardware and operating systems.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] External network virtualization combines or subdivides one or more local area networks (LANs) into virtual networks to improve a large network's or data center's efficiency.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] A virtual local area network (VLAN) and network switch comprise the key components.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Using this technology, a system administrator can configure systems physically attached to the same local network into separate virtual networks.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Conversely, an administrator can combine systems on separate local area networks (LANs) into a single VLAN spanning segments of a large network.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] External network virtualization is envisioned to be placed in the middle of the network stack and help integrating different architectures proposed for next generation networks.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Citrix and Vyatta have built a virtual network protocol stack combining Vyatta's routing, firewall, and VPN functions with Citrix's Netscaler load balancer, branch repeater wide area network (WAN) optimization, and secure sockets layer VPN.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] OpenSolaris network virtualization provides a so-called "network in a box" (see OpenSolaris Network Virtualization and Resource Control).
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Microsoft Virtual Server uses virtual machines to make a "network in a box" for x86 systems.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] These containers can run different operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows or Linux, either associated with or independent of a specific network interface controller (NIC).
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Network virtualization may be used in application development and testing to mimic real-world hardware and system software.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] In application performance engineering, network virtualization enables emulation of connections between applications, services, dependencies, and end users for software testing.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Wireless network virtualization can have a very broad scope ranging from spectrum sharing, infrastructure virtualization, to air interface virtualization.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] In other words, virtualization, regardless of wired or wireless networks, can be considered as a process splitting the entire network system.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] However, the distinctive properties of the wireless environment, in terms of time-various channels, attenuation, mobility, broadcast, etc., make the problem more complicated.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Therefore, it may be inaccurate to consider wireless network virtualization as a subset of network virtualization.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Until 1 Gbit/s networks, network virtualization was not suffering from the overhead of the software layers or hypervisor layers providing the interconnects.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] With the rise of high bandwidth, 10 Gbit/s and beyond, the rates of packets exceed the capabilities of processing of the networking stacks.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] For example, in case of Openstack, network is provided by Neutron which leverages many features from the Linux kernel for networking: iptables, iproute2, L2 bridge, L3 routing or OVS.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] Since the Linux kernel cannot sustain the 10G packet rate, then some bypass technologies for a fast path are used.
[src:network-slicing/network-virtualization] The main bypass technologies are either based on a limited set of features such as Open vSwitch (OVS) with its DPDK user space implementation or based on a full feature and offload of Linux processing such as 6WIND virtual accelerator.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:network-slicing/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] A **radio access network** (**RAN**) is part of a mobile telecommunication system implementing a radio access technology (RAT).
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] Conceptually, it resides between a device such as a mobile phone, a computer, or any remotely controlled machine and provides connection with its core network (CN).
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] Depending on the standard, mobile phones and other wireless connected devices are varyingly known as user equipment (UE), terminal equipment, mobile station (MS), etc.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] RAN functionality is typically provided by a silicon chip residing in both the core network as well as the user equipment.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] It is also possible for a single handset/phone to be simultaneously connected to multiple RANs.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] Handsets capable of this are sometimes called dual-mode handsets.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] For instance it is common for handsets to support both GSM and UMTS (a.k.a.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] Such devices seamlessly transfer an ongoing call between different radio access networks without the user noticing any disruption in service.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] According to research company New Street, mobile providers T-Mobile US and AT&T use Swedish communication company Ericsson as their primary RAN provider, while Verizon primarily uses South Korean provider Samsung.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] Nokia is the minority vendor for all major US wireless providers.
[src:network-slicing/radio-access-network] According to EJL Wireless Research, Verizon is also using Ericsson.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:network-slicing/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
